Starting with the initial year, the method normalizes the year to the first odd one that is equal to or greater the argument.  Subsequent years are increased by 2, skipping the even years since the first low order digit must be odd regardless of the others. This method simply iterates over the odd years until the one meeting the requirements is found. 
```
public static int closestOddYear(int year) {
    year += ((year &amp; 1) == 1) ? 0 : 1;
    while (!areDigitsOdd(year)) {
            year += 2;
    }
    return year;
}

```
This method just checks the `lsb` of each exposed digit to see if it is odd.  Since all odd numbers have the lower order bit set, this just ANDs 1 with that bit.  A result of `0` would indicate an even digit, and `1` would be odd. The method short circuits to `false` if any encountered digit is even.  Otherwise it returns `true`.
```
public static boolean areDigitsOdd(int year) {
    while (year &gt; 0) {
        if ((year &amp; 1) != 1) {
            return false;
        }
        year /= 10;
    }
    return true;
}

